WEBVTT

00:00.467 --> 00:01.600
engagement,
John.

00:01.602 --> 00:02.935
<i> I hope she makes you happy.</i>

00:05.139 --> 00:07.406
<i> - It's the clothing</i>
<i> the Napp baby wore.</i>

00:07.542 --> 00:10.743
- Steady hand.
Perhaps the work of a surgeon.

00:10.878 --> 00:13.612
- [baby cries]
<i> - A woman who lost the child.</i>

00:13.748 --> 00:15.948
- I care for Helen greatly,
Dr. Markoe,

00:16.083 --> 00:18.951
but I can't afford the scandal.

00:19.086 --> 00:21.820
<i> - Where is my baby?</i>
<i> I want to see her.</i>

00:21.822 --> 00:23.956
- Your child is with
the angels now, my dear.

00:24.091 --> 00:26.759
<i> Many of our staff</i>
<i> are simply ward girls,</i>

00:26.894 --> 00:29.695
who sadly often lose
their infants in childbirth.

00:29.830 --> 00:31.496
- May I ask you something,
nurse?

00:31.632 --> 00:33.298
- You can just call me Libby.

00:33.434 --> 00:35.768
<i> - What happened</i>
<i> at the hospital?</i>

00:35.903 --> 00:36.969
- No!

00:37.104 --> 00:38.437
<i> - I have the file</i>
<i> on Martha Napp</i>

00:38.439 --> 00:39.638
<i> from the Lying-In Hospital.</i>

00:39.774 --> 00:41.640
The last person to check
on Martha Napp

00:41.642 --> 00:43.943
<i> was an employee</i>
<i> named Colleen Ledwidge.</i>

00:46.714 --> 00:49.314
<i> [soft suspenseful music]</i>

00:49.450 --> 00:56.556
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:08.669 --> 01:11.336
- I was referred to you
by a wealthy family.

01:11.472 --> 01:14.607
- It's mainly the poor
who come in now.

01:14.742 --> 01:16.809
- Do you perform the service
pro bono?

01:16.944 --> 01:17.876
- I do.

01:17.878 --> 01:19.344
It'd be mercenary
to charge them

01:19.480 --> 01:21.747
when they've been through
so much.

01:21.749 --> 01:24.950
- I suspect your compassion
stems from a bereavement,

01:24.952 --> 01:25.818
Mrs. Carlisle.

01:25.953 --> 01:28.687
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:28.823 --> 01:30.489
- My William
departed this earth

01:30.625 --> 01:34.493
when he was six months old.

01:34.495 --> 01:37.230
Nothing compares
to losing an infant.

01:37.364 --> 01:42.034
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:42.169 --> 01:43.702
[horse neighs]

01:43.704 --> 01:45.838
- Remember, Bitsy,
if the killer is there,

01:45.973 --> 01:47.973
it will be crucial
to be inconspicuous.

01:47.975 --> 01:50.709
- I'll be fine, Miss Sara.
I can handle myself.

01:50.845 --> 01:52.711
I'll tell them I come
from a big family.

01:52.713 --> 01:54.513
Worked as a domestic, mostly,

01:54.649 --> 01:56.381
and a lot of the time,
I was with the babies.

01:56.517 --> 01:58.717
- No, tell them all you know
is babies.

01:58.853 --> 02:00.453
Liars embellish the truth.

02:00.588 --> 02:03.122
If you want to tell a good lie,
keep it simple.

02:03.257 --> 02:04.657
- I'll keep it simple, then.

02:04.792 --> 02:07.726
- It's best if you work
alongside the ward girls.

02:07.862 --> 02:09.194
That way,
you'll be able to listen

02:09.196 --> 02:11.931
to everything and everyone.

02:12.066 --> 02:14.399
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:14.535 --> 02:16.469
- Most of these images
conjure the illusion

02:16.603 --> 02:17.803
that the child
is merely sleeping,

02:17.805 --> 02:21.874
but...these images here...

02:22.009 --> 02:26.211
The eyes transform the picture
from a consolation to...

02:26.213 --> 02:28.481
something more disturbing.

02:28.615 --> 02:32.285
- The eyes are hand-painted
onto the negative.

02:32.419 --> 02:36.489
I've only made two of them
in all my years.

02:36.624 --> 02:38.691
- A grief
that defied understanding.

02:38.826 --> 02:41.160
- A grief without end.

02:41.296 --> 02:42.627
As if by painting the eyes,

02:42.629 --> 02:44.563
she could see through
to the soul.

02:44.565 --> 02:46.365
<i> [ominous notes]</i>

02:46.367 --> 02:49.234
- Where are the mothers now?

02:49.236 --> 02:51.236
- Took their own lives.

02:51.238 --> 02:52.838
They had that look.

02:52.974 --> 02:56.108
As if their spirits
had already departed this earth

02:56.243 --> 02:59.512
and they were mere shades.

02:59.646 --> 03:01.480
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:02.984 --> 03:05.851
[crying echoing]

03:05.987 --> 03:10.055
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:10.057 --> 03:13.592
<i> - Grief is a wound</i>
<i> that sometimes never heals.</i>

03:13.594 --> 03:16.195
I am correct, am I not?

03:16.197 --> 03:19.865
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:19.867 --> 03:24.269
- Memento mori.
- "Remember you will die."

03:24.271 --> 03:28.407
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:28.409 --> 03:31.410
<i> [dark music]</i>

03:31.412 --> 03:35.815
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:01.976 --> 04:05.011
[thunder rumbling]

04:20.595 --> 04:23.062
- I don't know why the "Times"
bothers reporting the weather

04:23.064 --> 04:24.997
when they are never
remotely correct.

04:25.132 --> 04:27.600
- Well, it's meant
to pass quickly.

04:27.735 --> 04:31.070
It's mostly bills, I think.

04:31.072 --> 04:33.005
This one's not.

04:43.550 --> 04:46.218
- Hello?
I'm here to see Miss Howard.

04:46.353 --> 04:49.222
- I'm Miss Howard's assistant.
She won't be a moment.

04:49.356 --> 04:50.890
- Libby.

04:54.629 --> 04:56.896
- Uh, Miss Howard,
if I could get the file back?

04:57.031 --> 05:01.366
I'm somewhat anxious about
being late to the hospital.

05:01.502 --> 05:04.503
Uh, Matron is so...

05:04.505 --> 05:06.571
unforgiving.

05:06.573 --> 05:08.040
- Come in.

05:14.181 --> 05:17.382
- Oh, my, it's quite the armory
you have here.

05:17.518 --> 05:19.652
- A legacy from my father.

05:21.656 --> 05:23.623
Have you read the file?

05:25.926 --> 05:28.593
Says that Colleen Ledwidge
was the last person

05:28.595 --> 05:29.728
to check on Martha Napp

05:29.864 --> 05:31.130
the night
her baby went missing.

05:31.265 --> 05:34.800
- She was on duty that night.
Did her rounds.

05:37.938 --> 05:40.139
I'm not a gossip, Miss Howard.

05:47.682 --> 05:49.748
People who can't stand up
for themselves

05:49.884 --> 05:53.953
are often unhappily blamed
for the sins of others.

05:57.959 --> 05:59.091
- Libby.

05:59.226 --> 06:01.226
Do you think
that Colleen is capable

06:01.362 --> 06:02.962
of kidnapping a baby?

06:03.097 --> 06:05.965
Of murder?

06:06.100 --> 06:09.168
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

06:09.304 --> 06:12.838
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:12.974 --> 06:15.107
- Where's the baby?

06:15.242 --> 06:17.977
- Stillborn.

06:17.979 --> 06:19.912
But he gives us some fish

06:20.047 --> 06:22.548
and a spot of greenery
to feel better.

06:25.252 --> 06:28.521
He must like her more
than he did me.

06:28.656 --> 06:31.857
Richard Osgood.

06:31.859 --> 06:34.459
I was given the bonsai first.

06:34.461 --> 06:37.596
Followed by some spotfin betta.

06:37.598 --> 06:39.264
See, they like
to get you pregnant

06:39.266 --> 06:41.066
to prove to their fellow
financial-types

06:41.068 --> 06:43.802
that their pecker still works.

06:43.804 --> 06:47.206
Set you up in an apartment
with fancy clothes and such.

06:47.342 --> 06:49.542
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:49.677 --> 06:51.476
- I'm sorry.

06:51.478 --> 06:52.545
- [scoffs]

06:52.680 --> 06:54.813
- Aren't we supposed
to bathe her?

06:54.949 --> 06:57.282
- He's had her fixed.

06:57.418 --> 06:59.484
Let's leave her sleep
as long as she can.

06:59.620 --> 07:06.491
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:06.627 --> 07:09.494
- [sobbing]

07:09.630 --> 07:14.367
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:14.501 --> 07:16.301
[baby crying distantly]

07:16.437 --> 07:23.342
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:33.388 --> 07:35.654
- Check with Dr. Markoe first.

07:35.656 --> 07:38.257
- Yes, Matron.
- [sighs]

07:38.259 --> 07:41.794
What are you doing, Libby?
- Nothing, Matron.

07:41.929 --> 07:44.463
There was a body on the track
this morning.

07:44.599 --> 07:47.400
That's why I was late.

07:47.534 --> 07:50.469
The tram, it hit a dodger.

07:50.605 --> 07:52.471
- Get out.
- Sorry.

07:52.607 --> 07:54.539
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:54.541 --> 07:56.275
- Get to work.

07:56.411 --> 08:02.347
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:02.483 --> 08:05.684
Stupid, stupid.

08:05.686 --> 08:12.859
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:16.230 --> 08:18.563
- We believe the kidnapper
is a nursing woman

08:18.565 --> 08:20.165
or had an abettor who was.

08:20.167 --> 08:22.768
Either way, they were slow to--
- Loathe, I'd argue.

08:22.903 --> 08:23.903
- To kill.

08:24.038 --> 08:25.638
- I don't understand.

08:25.773 --> 08:28.240
- It has to do with a black
stain on the child's dress.

08:28.375 --> 08:30.443
It is carbon.
Powdered charcoal.

08:30.577 --> 08:32.377
- It is used as an antidote
to the poison.

08:32.379 --> 08:34.113
- We found both the antidote
and the poison

08:34.115 --> 08:35.448
in the child's stomach.

08:35.583 --> 08:37.716
- This may be interesting
for the Napp baby,

08:37.852 --> 08:40.519
whom you did not save,

08:40.655 --> 08:43.188
but you've done nothing for us.

08:43.190 --> 08:45.190
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

08:45.192 --> 08:48.060
- Like you, Señor,
I'm not of this place.

08:48.195 --> 08:50.062
Other than you,
having the added burden

08:50.197 --> 08:51.664
of being seen
as an enemy of the state,

08:51.799 --> 08:55.001
you and I experience
American authority similarly.

08:57.204 --> 08:59.738
- The police are not interested
in finding your child, Señor.

08:59.874 --> 09:02.675
They think you staged
the kidnapping yourself.

09:02.810 --> 09:04.009
- I can corroborate that.

09:04.145 --> 09:06.345
- We are your detectives
on this case, sir.

09:06.481 --> 09:09.148
- Please, let me present
to you our theories

09:09.284 --> 09:10.950
and tell you the steps
that we are taking.

09:11.085 --> 09:15.020
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:15.156 --> 09:17.690
We have identified the poison
used to kill the baby,

09:17.825 --> 09:19.024
and we know
that the key ingredient

09:19.026 --> 09:21.026
cannot be obtained
outside of a hospital,

09:21.162 --> 09:22.561
one hospital in particular.

09:22.563 --> 09:25.964
- From which the Napp baby
was removed.

09:25.966 --> 09:27.366
- But you're all here.

09:27.368 --> 09:31.770
- We have someone undercover
at this very moment.

09:31.906 --> 09:35.574
- If the doctor instructs you
to administer more chloroform,

09:35.710 --> 09:36.842
you do so!

09:36.844 --> 09:37.843
- She was refusing, ma'am.

09:37.979 --> 09:42.515
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:42.650 --> 09:44.984
- You may finish the mopping.

09:44.986 --> 09:46.919
- I don't understand
what I have done wrong.

09:47.054 --> 09:50.389
- I know what you were doing
in my office.

09:50.525 --> 09:53.792
Now, mop the floor!

09:53.794 --> 09:56.795
<i> [soft tense music]</i>

09:56.797 --> 09:59.064
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:59.200 --> 10:02.735
Take your apron off first,
and then do it.

10:02.870 --> 10:05.070
You are stupid!

10:05.206 --> 10:08.607
Stupid, stupid, stupid.

10:08.609 --> 10:10.475
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:10.477 --> 10:13.412
[indistinct chatter]

10:17.218 --> 10:18.951
- Who in blazes
turned my building

10:19.086 --> 10:21.153
into a flower market?

10:21.288 --> 10:24.423
- I believe
you ordered them, sir.

10:24.559 --> 10:26.091
For Miss Violet's party.

10:26.093 --> 10:29.228
- And you should've told me
what a godawful idea it was.

10:30.831 --> 10:32.898
- Yes, chief.

10:32.900 --> 10:35.034
- Thank you.
Thank you very much, sir.

10:35.036 --> 10:36.702
Madam!
Hunter of a torso!

10:36.704 --> 10:40.206
[indistinct chatter]

10:46.447 --> 10:48.914
- Did you hear Millbank
has lent his Rhinebeck place

10:48.916 --> 10:51.050
to the blockade planning?

10:51.185 --> 10:53.852
Navy and Army
are bunking up there.

10:53.988 --> 10:55.254
- Now, how would
a lowlife like me

10:55.256 --> 10:56.655
get access to that information?

10:56.791 --> 10:58.724
- Oh, I would've thought
it would've trickled down

10:58.726 --> 11:01.927
to the masses by now.

11:01.929 --> 11:05.364
- Mr. Moore?
- Joanna, right on time.

11:07.468 --> 11:08.934
- This is the girl you--

11:08.936 --> 11:10.736
- Bernie,
this is Joanna Crawford.

11:10.871 --> 11:13.072
- Pleased to meet you.

11:13.074 --> 11:15.875
- How on earth
will she be gathering stories

11:16.010 --> 11:17.410
for the society pages, John?

11:17.544 --> 11:19.678
- I will apprise Joanna
of the event

11:19.814 --> 11:22.281
and she will write it up.

11:22.283 --> 11:23.949
We'll manage brilliantly,
won't we?

11:23.951 --> 11:26.018
- Yes.

11:26.153 --> 11:28.020
- You really wrote
that article on--

11:28.155 --> 11:29.688
- "Suffragism
and Emancipation:

11:29.824 --> 11:31.023
A New America"?

11:31.158 --> 11:34.559
That was my senior thesis.
- It was...

11:34.695 --> 11:36.762
It was very good.

11:36.897 --> 11:37.896
- Thank you, sir.

11:37.898 --> 11:39.031
I'm very passionate about--

11:39.166 --> 11:40.533
- We should show you
the office.

11:45.372 --> 11:48.941
- Okay.
Carry on, then.

11:51.646 --> 11:54.713
[hymnal organ music]

11:54.715 --> 12:01.888
♪ ♪

12:05.192 --> 12:07.927
- I wasn't sure you could come.

12:08.062 --> 12:09.394
- I couldn't leave till now

12:09.396 --> 12:11.396
without anybody
getting suspicious.

12:11.398 --> 12:12.865
- What have you discovered?

12:13.000 --> 12:16.469
Have you learned anything about
the maternal research wing?

12:16.603 --> 12:18.471
- It's where they keep
the pregnant mistresses

12:18.606 --> 12:20.606
of rich old men.

12:20.741 --> 12:24.943
What's more the peculiar is,
there's no babies up there.

12:24.945 --> 12:26.812
- Why?
Where are they?

12:26.947 --> 12:28.347
- That's the thing.

12:28.349 --> 12:31.083
The women up there now,
they all had stillborns.

12:31.218 --> 12:33.653
- All of them?
- That's what they tell them.

12:35.290 --> 12:37.490
- What can you tell me
about Colleen Ledwidge?

12:37.625 --> 12:39.424
- Well, she's one
of the ward girls.

12:39.426 --> 12:40.826
Pretty tough character.

12:40.828 --> 12:43.696
- Markoe seems to have
a special interest in her.

12:43.831 --> 12:44.897
- Mm.

12:45.032 --> 12:46.632
- Bide your time.

12:46.767 --> 12:50.503
Become friends with her.
Get her to confide in you.

12:52.640 --> 12:55.374
- You see, the only thing
is something she said.

12:55.376 --> 12:58.243
She's a ward girl,
but she started as a patient.

12:58.379 --> 13:01.446
This big-time swell
Richard Osgood knocked her up.

13:01.582 --> 13:03.716
Another one of his girls,
Helen Sumner,

13:03.851 --> 13:06.319
came in to the research wing
yesterday.

13:06.453 --> 13:11.256
♪ ♪

13:11.258 --> 13:14.193
- Was Colleen's baby
also stillborn?

13:14.195 --> 13:17.129
- I didn't ask her.
- See if you can find out.

13:17.264 --> 13:18.531
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:18.666 --> 13:20.666
There's something else
I want you to do.

13:20.668 --> 13:21.534
- Sure, what is it?

13:21.669 --> 13:23.336
- The Isaacsons
identified the poison

13:23.470 --> 13:25.538
found in the body
of the Napp child.

13:25.673 --> 13:27.673
I want you to see
where it's stored.

13:27.808 --> 13:29.942
- The drugs are kept
under lock and key,

13:30.077 --> 13:31.944
but that's not a problem.

13:32.079 --> 13:35.014
There ain't a lock invented
that I can't pick, Miss Sara.

13:35.149 --> 13:36.481
- [chuckles]

13:36.617 --> 13:38.283
They said
they're aniline derivatives,

13:38.285 --> 13:39.484
but they may have
different names,

13:39.620 --> 13:42.221
so here's what
you're looking for.

13:42.357 --> 13:46.359
- Acetanilide phenacetin.

13:46.493 --> 13:49.828
- There should be a ledger
indicating drug administration.

13:49.830 --> 13:53.899
♪ ♪

13:54.035 --> 13:55.368
Maybe who signed for it.

13:55.502 --> 13:59.172
Look for names, amounts,
and who takes it out.

13:59.306 --> 14:02.175
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

14:02.309 --> 14:09.482
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:14.789 --> 14:17.723
[distant clanging]

14:26.267 --> 14:33.372
<i> ♪ </i>

15:15.049 --> 15:16.449
[latch clanks]

15:16.583 --> 15:19.384
- Oh, you gave me
such a fright. [chuckles]

15:19.386 --> 15:20.853
I thought my heart
was gonna explode.

15:20.988 --> 15:22.855
- What are you doing?

15:22.990 --> 15:24.256
- Nothing.

15:24.391 --> 15:25.858
- Oh, well, you're going
to get into bother

15:25.993 --> 15:26.859
if you're found in here.

15:26.994 --> 15:29.394
It's off-limits.

15:29.530 --> 15:31.263
But you already know that,
don't you?

15:31.398 --> 15:33.398
- No, no, I was looking for--

15:33.400 --> 15:35.734
- Oh, I believe you, then.

15:35.870 --> 15:38.537
<i> [ominous notes]</i>

15:38.539 --> 15:41.674
- Colleen Ledwidge.
Ward girl, grieving mother.

15:41.809 --> 15:42.808
She lost a baby,

15:42.810 --> 15:44.343
so she replaces it
with another one.

15:44.479 --> 15:46.679
- Kidnapping the Lindares child
is servicing a need,

15:46.814 --> 15:48.147
but there is a violence
to this case,

15:48.283 --> 15:50.015
a fury seething within
the murderer's breast.

15:50.151 --> 15:53.286
- Bitsy said she was enraged
at the wealthy man

15:53.420 --> 15:54.887
who had discarded her,
Richard Osgood.

15:55.022 --> 15:56.489
She fits our profile.

15:56.623 --> 15:58.624
- Could a ward girl acquire
aniline without detection?

15:58.759 --> 16:00.359
- The Matron oversees the ward.

16:00.361 --> 16:02.027
She no doubt places
the drug orders herself.

16:02.163 --> 16:03.496
She seems the most likely

16:03.631 --> 16:05.030
to have the access
and the means to cover it up.

16:05.032 --> 16:06.765
- Matron wields her power
at the hospital

16:06.901 --> 16:08.367
with spite and venom.

16:08.369 --> 16:11.036
Resentful, perhaps,
of what she does not have:

16:11.172 --> 16:12.505
A child.

16:14.241 --> 16:17.642
- Although a woman who is a wet
nurse better suits the profile.

16:17.644 --> 16:20.112
- The Matron manages
a staff of wet nurses

16:20.247 --> 16:21.981
who bottle their milk.

16:21.983 --> 16:24.717
She could administer that milk
to an infant if she wanted to.

16:24.852 --> 16:26.785
- I'd like us to not
lose sight of Markoe.

16:26.921 --> 16:28.854
- Laszlo, the psychology
of the profile fits a woman,

16:28.990 --> 16:30.655
and the evidence points
to one of these two.

16:30.657 --> 16:32.457
- But Markoe oversees
the Matron.

16:32.459 --> 16:33.592
He may not have taken
the child,

16:33.728 --> 16:35.828
but undoubtedly he knows more.

16:36.998 --> 16:38.931
- Well, as a cherished friend
of The 400,

16:39.066 --> 16:42.467
he will be attending
the social event of the season,

16:42.469 --> 16:44.203
as will Richard Osgood.

16:44.339 --> 16:48.273
- You can't mean to ambush them
at Mr. Moore's party.

16:48.275 --> 16:49.808
- It's our opportunity.

16:49.944 --> 16:53.078
It's not ideal,
but John will understand.

16:53.214 --> 16:54.479
- Will he?

16:54.615 --> 16:56.682
- We can't simply stand
on ceremony, Laszlo.

16:56.817 --> 16:58.684
What these two mean reveal
about these suspects

16:58.686 --> 17:00.553
could lead us to baby Ana.

17:05.293 --> 17:08.260
<i> [classical music]</i>

17:08.262 --> 17:15.434
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:34.422 --> 17:36.355
- I must confess,
it does feel strange

17:36.357 --> 17:37.623
to be attending a ball

17:37.758 --> 17:39.958
while there is a child
still missing.

17:39.960 --> 17:42.895
[indistinct chatter]

17:42.897 --> 17:49.869
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:54.508 --> 17:55.775
[dog barks]

18:00.981 --> 18:03.216
Over there.

18:05.386 --> 18:07.319
I should say hello
to our hosts.

18:07.455 --> 18:08.721
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:08.856 --> 18:12.591
Where are you going?
- To observe our friend.

18:12.593 --> 18:15.794
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:15.930 --> 18:17.430
[match sizzles]

18:18.933 --> 18:23.870
- Sir, if you link the Linares
abduction to Spain and Cuba,

18:24.004 --> 18:26.272
there is a chance
you may spook the kidnappers.

18:26.407 --> 18:29.408
- So you think
there are kidnappers then?

18:29.543 --> 18:32.010
- No, sir, not necessarily,
but it--

18:32.012 --> 18:33.946
- [chuckles]

18:34.082 --> 18:36.682
Richard, the man is marrying
my own goddaughter,

18:36.817 --> 18:39.017
and here he is hiding a story.

18:39.153 --> 18:41.353
- You know I work
for the "New York Times."

18:41.355 --> 18:42.555
- The opposition.

18:42.690 --> 18:44.356
- The Linares
are clearly guilty.

18:44.492 --> 18:46.492
- Guilty of what?
- Who knows, Moore?

18:46.627 --> 18:49.828
Guilty of neglect,
conspiracy, fraud.

18:49.964 --> 18:52.698
I wouldn't put anything
past them, even murder.

18:52.833 --> 18:54.567
And perhaps the child
is back in Spain

18:54.702 --> 18:56.302
and they're using this
as an opportunity

18:56.437 --> 18:58.904
to gain sympathy
from the American public.

18:59.039 --> 19:01.240
Well, they won't get it
from the "Journal," Moore.

19:01.375 --> 19:03.041
That I can assure you.

19:03.043 --> 19:04.643
- Mr. Hearst,

19:04.779 --> 19:08.247
I honestly believe the Linares
family are innocent.

19:08.382 --> 19:09.916
I would only ask
that whatever line

19:10.050 --> 19:11.717
the "Journal" takes
on this story,

19:11.852 --> 19:13.919
this tragedy is not used
to drum up support

19:14.054 --> 19:15.854
against the Spanish
for the war in Cuba.

19:15.990 --> 19:18.724
- War with Spain over Cuba
is going to happen.

19:18.859 --> 19:20.459
- I think that's enough
for politics

19:20.461 --> 19:22.295
for tonight, Osgood.

19:24.198 --> 19:25.864
Okay, Moore.

19:25.866 --> 19:29.869
I'm sure Violet
is waiting for you.

19:37.812 --> 19:41.013
- It's Byrnes here
to see you, chief.

19:41.149 --> 19:44.550
- Ah, Byrnes, my man.
I wasn't expecting you tonight.

19:44.685 --> 19:46.619
- I've come to pay my respects,
Mr. Hearst.

19:46.754 --> 19:48.420
I brung you a gift.

19:48.556 --> 19:50.957
It's for your goddaughter
and her betrothed.

19:51.091 --> 19:53.426
- [chuckles]
- Stop it, Richard.

19:55.763 --> 19:57.563
- Mr. Osgood.

19:57.698 --> 19:59.365
- I don't believe I know you.

19:59.500 --> 20:02.168
- Oh, I know you, sir.
[chuckles] I know you.

20:02.302 --> 20:04.770
- Mr. Byrnes is my go-to man
for all sensitive matters.

20:04.905 --> 20:08.774
He is very effective
and very discreet.

20:08.909 --> 20:11.777
Thank you for the gift, Byrnes.
Very considerate of you.

20:11.912 --> 20:13.912
Just leave it with Monckton.

20:14.048 --> 20:15.581
- Uh, sir, um...

20:15.716 --> 20:18.316
these are some
very fine cigars, sir.

20:18.318 --> 20:21.053
- Well, Violet fill find it
a wheeze, I'm sure.

20:21.189 --> 20:23.856
Monckton!
- Chief?

20:29.397 --> 20:30.863
- Sir.

20:30.865 --> 20:32.331
- You can help yourself
to some hors d'oeuvres

20:32.466 --> 20:34.000
in the kitchen on your way out.

20:37.805 --> 20:41.707
[sighs]
- I'll take that, Byrnes.

20:43.077 --> 20:46.545
- That's former
Chief Commissioner Byrnes

20:46.547 --> 20:48.480
to you, Monckton.

20:48.616 --> 20:50.016
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:50.150 --> 20:51.017
[chuckles]

20:51.151 --> 20:52.484
But hey,
I won't hold that against you.

20:52.620 --> 20:54.020
Put it there.

20:56.757 --> 20:58.490
Maybe your mother didn't
teach you manners

20:58.626 --> 21:00.759
growing up, Monckton,

21:00.761 --> 21:02.695
so I'll forgive you for that.

21:02.697 --> 21:04.030
I don't expect you to like me,

21:04.164 --> 21:08.434
but what I do require
is some respect.

21:08.569 --> 21:12.170
And a modicum of civility.

21:12.306 --> 21:19.412
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

21:30.658 --> 21:33.525
- Picking up any gossip?
- Mm-hmm.

21:33.527 --> 21:40.700
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:09.764 --> 22:10.963
- Remind me again

22:10.965 --> 22:13.966
what your costume is,
Miss Howard.

22:14.102 --> 22:16.569
- I'm a lady undercover
on a Sunday stroll.

22:16.704 --> 22:19.305
- [chuckles]
No one would ever guess.

22:19.440 --> 22:22.641
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:22.777 --> 22:24.643
- I have much to tell you.

22:24.779 --> 22:26.579
I suppose you know
that Markoe is here.

22:26.714 --> 22:28.714
- Yes, I'm very aware of that.

22:28.849 --> 22:32.584
- Laszlo and I have agreed
to talk to him tonight.

22:32.586 --> 22:34.787
- Sara, we have nothing
to confront him with

22:34.922 --> 22:37.255
except
unsubstantiated suppositions.

22:37.257 --> 22:39.325
- Need I remind you that there
is a child missing?

22:39.460 --> 22:40.726
- And need I remind you

22:40.861 --> 22:43.930
that this is
my engagement party?

22:44.064 --> 22:45.531
The only thing
you are succeeding doing

22:45.666 --> 22:48.066
is embarrassing Violet.

22:48.202 --> 22:49.468
- Ah, Miss Howard.

22:49.603 --> 22:51.737
[chuckles]
How lovely to see you.

22:51.872 --> 22:53.539
Has my card made its way
to you yet?

22:53.674 --> 22:55.474
- My apologies,
Mr. Gildersleeve.

22:55.476 --> 22:58.611
My boss, Mr. Moore here,
has kept me so terribly busy

22:58.746 --> 23:01.147
that I haven't had a chance
to reply.

23:01.282 --> 23:02.414
- [chuckles softly]

23:02.550 --> 23:04.282
[electricity zaps]
- [clinks glass]

23:04.284 --> 23:06.218
Hello, friends!

23:06.220 --> 23:09.555
Thank you so much for joining
us on this auspicious evening.

23:09.690 --> 23:11.089
I am so pleased

23:11.225 --> 23:12.825
to be able to honor
my goddaughter, Violet,

23:12.961 --> 23:17.296
and soon-to-be godson-in-law,
John Moore,

23:17.431 --> 23:21.500
even though he has chosen
a very wrongheaded career path.

23:21.636 --> 23:24.170
[laughter]

23:24.304 --> 23:25.704
Where is John?

23:25.706 --> 23:27.706
- Down here and dressed as--

23:27.842 --> 23:30.176
- A cub reporter
for the "New York Times."

23:30.311 --> 23:31.644
[laughter]

23:31.646 --> 23:33.445
- All the news
that's fit to print?

23:33.447 --> 23:35.914
Your Mr. Peterson misses the
biggest stories in this city

23:36.050 --> 23:38.718
on the daily.
[laughter]

23:42.056 --> 23:44.657
- I thought the roast was saved
for the wedding dinner, sir.

23:44.659 --> 23:49.061
- Oh, this is my soap box, boy.
I'll say what pleases me.

23:49.063 --> 23:52.264
But perhaps you'll forgive
my gentle ribbing

23:52.400 --> 23:53.900
when I present you this.

23:55.536 --> 23:56.735
[oohs and ahhs]

23:56.737 --> 23:58.704
[applause]

24:01.009 --> 24:04.677
The very first German-designed
luxury motorcar

24:04.812 --> 24:06.345
to hit our shore.

24:06.480 --> 24:08.881
I have no need to extol
its many virtues to you, John.

24:09.017 --> 24:11.884
- John's been extolling
the virtues of public transit.

24:12.020 --> 24:14.220
- Because he can't afford
an automobile.

24:14.355 --> 24:16.154
[laughter]

24:16.290 --> 24:17.289
- Now, boys.

24:17.291 --> 24:19.892
I am dusting him off
and spiffing him up.

24:20.028 --> 24:22.895
The car is just one part
of the costume.

24:22.897 --> 24:24.430
No more need to bother
Miss Howard

24:24.565 --> 24:26.298
for jaunts here and there.

24:26.300 --> 24:28.767
- Three cheers
for the Hearst largesse!

24:28.903 --> 24:30.903
- Hip, hip--
all: Hurrah!

24:30.905 --> 24:32.905
- Hip, hip--
all: Hurrah!

24:32.907 --> 24:36.442
- Hip, hip--
all: Hurrah!

24:36.577 --> 24:39.445
[laughter and applause]

24:39.580 --> 24:42.448
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

24:42.583 --> 24:49.455
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

24:49.590 --> 24:52.458
<i> [classical music]</i>

24:52.593 --> 24:57.163
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:05.339 --> 25:07.873
- The three agencies of action
within human nature

25:08.008 --> 25:09.742
are appetite, spirit,
and reason.

25:09.744 --> 25:11.143
Before me, I see

25:11.145 --> 25:14.546
appetite has vanquished
both spirit and reason.

25:14.548 --> 25:17.550
- I know who you are.
You're that damned alienist.

25:17.685 --> 25:20.419
- You've had quite the harem
at the Lying-In Hospital.

25:20.554 --> 25:21.620
A new girl

25:21.756 --> 25:22.955
in the research wing,
I understand?

25:22.957 --> 25:24.423
- Have you been spying on me?

25:24.558 --> 25:26.759
I can have you removed
from not only this party,

25:26.894 --> 25:29.295
but from the country
as a foreign undesirable.

25:29.430 --> 25:32.098
- A child went missing
from the hospital. Murdered.

25:32.232 --> 25:33.632
The killer has taken
another one.

25:33.634 --> 25:35.434
- Damn you, man.
This has nothing to do with me.

25:35.436 --> 25:37.436
- It has everything to do
with you, Osgood.

25:37.438 --> 25:39.305
To you, these girls
are merely playthings.

25:39.440 --> 25:42.240
- What of it?
They are hardly innocent.

25:42.242 --> 25:45.511
- Tell me, what do you know
of Colleen Ledwidge?

25:45.646 --> 25:48.046
<i> [soft tense music]</i>

25:48.048 --> 25:52.718
- You think Colleen,
Miss Ledwidge,

25:52.853 --> 25:55.521
is responsible
for these crimes?

25:55.656 --> 25:57.456
Colleen worked in service.

25:57.458 --> 26:00.392
She was impressed
by fine clothes, a dinner out.

26:00.394 --> 26:03.195
Perhaps I persuaded her to
think that my intentions were--

26:03.331 --> 26:05.798
- Honorable?

26:05.934 --> 26:07.866
Is she violent?

26:07.868 --> 26:10.136
- Hot-blooded.
Feisty.

26:10.271 --> 26:11.804
Like a mare
that needs breaking in.

26:11.806 --> 26:13.139
- So you broke her in?

26:13.273 --> 26:14.540
- She didn't understand
the rules.

26:14.675 --> 26:15.874
- What are the rules?

26:15.876 --> 26:16.943
You take her innocence,
her youth,

26:17.077 --> 26:18.877
her prospects
in respectable society,

26:18.879 --> 26:20.612
and then you have her child
taken off her

26:20.614 --> 26:22.748
and sent God knows where?

26:22.883 --> 26:24.216
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:24.218 --> 26:27.086
- I thought her child had died.

26:28.689 --> 26:31.690
- A time for reckoning
comes to us all.

26:31.826 --> 26:35.962
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:37.832 --> 26:40.699
<i> [classical music]</i>

26:40.835 --> 26:47.940
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:59.920 --> 27:02.254
- I'm concerned
you're being bought, John,

27:02.390 --> 27:04.523
on the cusp
of your true independence,

27:04.525 --> 27:06.859
on the finding
of your own powerful words.

27:06.995 --> 27:09.161
I fear you're being seduced.

27:11.131 --> 27:12.331
- Well, I fear you're behaving

27:12.333 --> 27:14.901
like an irritating
sister, Sara.

27:16.470 --> 27:19.605
How about,
"What a lovely party, John.

27:19.740 --> 27:22.408
Please extend my thanks
to your generous bride-to-be."

27:22.543 --> 27:25.678
- Generous?
She humiliated you.

27:25.813 --> 27:29.348
- She did not humiliate me.
- She laughed at your expense.

27:29.483 --> 27:31.149
- It was a moment or two
of teasing.

27:31.285 --> 27:32.618
- That debased you.

27:32.753 --> 27:36.355
- If I'm not fussed by it,
then why should you be?

27:36.490 --> 27:38.624
You don't care about me
particularly.

27:38.759 --> 27:42.428
You made that quite clear
when I asked you to marry me.

27:42.563 --> 27:44.963
You said no, if you recall.

27:45.099 --> 27:47.966
<i> [downbeat music]</i>

27:48.102 --> 27:50.436
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:50.571 --> 27:54.907
- She's unkind to you,
in public, no less,

27:55.043 --> 27:57.776
which is not right
for you, John.

27:57.912 --> 27:59.645
Don't you see?

27:59.780 --> 28:01.113
You deserve someone

28:01.115 --> 28:02.981
who is adventurous
and curious and--

28:03.117 --> 28:05.584
- Someone like you?

28:05.586 --> 28:07.920
- Yes.

28:07.922 --> 28:10.857
Someone like me.

28:10.991 --> 28:13.459
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:13.594 --> 28:15.461
But not me.

28:15.596 --> 28:20.867
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:21.001 --> 28:23.669
- A yazoo tributary.

28:23.804 --> 28:25.337
- What?

28:25.473 --> 28:27.673
- It's an Indian name
for a tributary

28:27.808 --> 28:29.608
that runs beside a main river.

28:29.610 --> 28:31.944
It flirts with joining it.

28:31.946 --> 28:34.813
It comes very close,
but never does.

28:34.949 --> 28:37.149
- A woman exactly like that,

28:37.151 --> 28:39.285
untied to the suffocating
social mores,

28:39.420 --> 28:41.820
the very opposite of any number
of women down there.

28:41.822 --> 28:44.690
- And the opposite of you too.

28:44.825 --> 28:48.694
So full of judgment,
yet trussed up like a turkey

28:48.829 --> 28:51.697
in your corset
and your fancy dress.

28:51.832 --> 28:52.899
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:53.033 --> 28:56.568
I decided, unlike you,

28:56.570 --> 29:01.307
that I want not to be alone,
childless, lonely,

29:01.442 --> 29:03.241
corseted.

29:03.243 --> 29:06.712
You're no yazoo tributary,
Sara Howard.

29:06.847 --> 29:09.115
In fact,

29:09.249 --> 29:12.785
you're swimming right down
the middle of the stream.

29:12.787 --> 29:18.191
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

29:28.836 --> 29:31.636
- Thanks for not
ratting me out to Matron.

29:31.638 --> 29:34.039
I didn't know
it was the drugs closet.

29:34.175 --> 29:35.908
- That's okay.

29:36.043 --> 29:39.979
We gotta stick together
around here.

29:39.981 --> 29:42.581
I got secrets too, you know?

29:42.717 --> 29:45.584
Not good ones.

29:45.720 --> 29:48.721
- Did you do something wrong?

29:48.856 --> 29:50.789
- Did I say it was me
that did something wrong?

29:50.791 --> 29:54.126
- No, just...

29:54.261 --> 29:57.196
[whispers] I thought you were
talking about you and Markoe.

29:57.332 --> 29:58.864
<i> [soft tense music]</i>

29:58.866 --> 30:01.334
- M-me and Markoe?

30:01.468 --> 30:08.341
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:10.211 --> 30:13.546
- Colleen pretends to herself
it doesn't happen.

30:13.681 --> 30:14.947
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:15.082 --> 30:17.350
You don't ask her
about things like that.

30:17.484 --> 30:19.885
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

30:19.887 --> 30:22.421
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:22.557 --> 30:24.690
You should say sorry.

30:24.692 --> 30:31.831
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:39.774 --> 30:41.974
[door handle shuffles]

30:42.109 --> 30:45.178
- What are you doing?
You need to be in bed.

30:45.312 --> 30:47.180
- Please help me.

30:47.314 --> 30:52.851
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:52.987 --> 30:56.121
I believed
all the sweet nothings.

30:56.257 --> 30:59.458
He can't throw me away
so easily.

30:59.460 --> 31:01.727
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:01.862 --> 31:03.462
Help me.

31:03.598 --> 31:10.736
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:24.419 --> 31:27.486
[oohs and ahhs]

31:27.488 --> 31:29.888
[indistinct chatter]

31:29.890 --> 31:32.291
[cheers and applause]

31:32.293 --> 31:33.426
[shushing]

31:33.560 --> 31:37.096
- Where's Violet?
- She said we could go ahead.

31:46.641 --> 31:48.441
- V?

31:48.576 --> 31:50.309
- Lock the door.

31:50.311 --> 31:55.248
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:55.382 --> 31:57.783
- I do hope this
is the only key to the room.

31:57.918 --> 32:00.853
- Not absolutely, totally sure,

32:00.988 --> 32:03.255
which makes it
all the more exciting.

32:03.390 --> 32:04.857
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

32:04.992 --> 32:08.261
- On your marks!
- Come on!

32:08.395 --> 32:10.796
- Get set!

32:10.931 --> 32:12.798
both: Go!

32:12.800 --> 32:14.800
[crowd hooting and clamoring]

32:14.935 --> 32:16.869
- Get the ring!

32:17.004 --> 32:20.739
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:20.875 --> 32:23.809
- Are you mad?

32:23.944 --> 32:26.211
[chuckles]
My God, woman.

32:26.213 --> 32:28.347
What has possessed you?

32:28.349 --> 32:34.754
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:36.423 --> 32:37.756
- Find the ring!

32:37.758 --> 32:40.559
[cheers]
- I found the ring!

32:40.695 --> 32:42.761
- Whoo-hoo-hoo-hoo-hoo!

32:42.763 --> 32:46.098
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:46.233 --> 32:48.501
- It's more than
somewhat depressing.

32:48.636 --> 32:53.038
Such wanton extravagance
fills me with melancholia.

32:53.040 --> 32:55.841
[indistinct clamor, cheers]

32:55.977 --> 32:57.310
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:57.444 --> 32:59.044
It's like Versailles.

32:59.046 --> 33:02.114
So far, I have counted
three Louis Quatorzes

33:02.249 --> 33:04.984
and at least four
Marie Antoinettes.

33:05.119 --> 33:08.453
What was it she said
to her starving subjects?

33:08.455 --> 33:12.591
"If you don't have bread,
let them eat cake."

33:12.593 --> 33:14.860
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

33:14.862 --> 33:16.662
- I think
what she actually said was,

33:16.797 --> 33:18.130
"Qu'ils mangent de la brioche,"

33:18.265 --> 33:20.132
which is
"Let them eat brioche."

33:20.267 --> 33:22.735
Although, of course,
brioche is a pastry of sorts

33:22.870 --> 33:25.270
and at the time,
probably meant cake.

33:25.272 --> 33:26.739
And I don't mean
to be pedantic,

33:26.874 --> 33:30.209
but I think you'll find there's
only three Marie Antoinettes,

33:30.211 --> 33:31.476
not four.

33:31.478 --> 33:34.947
I think the one by that
monstrosity of a motorcar

33:35.082 --> 33:37.216
is actually
a Madame de Pompadour,

33:37.352 --> 33:42.221
chief mistress of Louis XV,
rather than a Marie Antoinette,

33:42.223 --> 33:45.891
although your error
is entirely understandable.

33:45.893 --> 33:47.226
- Chief mistress?

33:47.228 --> 33:50.429
- Yes, it was an actual
royal court position,

33:50.565 --> 33:52.431
believe it or not.

33:52.433 --> 33:54.700
And who are you,
and what do you do,

33:54.702 --> 33:56.369
and how do you come to be here?

33:56.503 --> 33:57.770
- I'm an alienist.

33:57.905 --> 33:59.705
- As am I.

33:59.707 --> 34:00.839
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:00.975 --> 34:03.242
- [chuckles]
You're teasing me.

34:03.244 --> 34:05.110
- Yes, I'm teasing you.

34:05.246 --> 34:06.979
But it's also true.

34:07.114 --> 34:09.048
Karen Stratton.

34:09.183 --> 34:11.984
I was Violet's professor
at Barnard.

34:12.119 --> 34:13.719
Well, she had me
for a semester.

34:13.854 --> 34:17.723
- Professor Karen Stratton.
I've read all your work.

34:17.725 --> 34:18.857
- I'm Doctor--

34:18.993 --> 34:20.259
- Of course,
I know you're Dr. Kreizler.

34:20.261 --> 34:22.595
Who in New York
hasn't heard of you?

34:22.730 --> 34:24.597
And in fact, it seems as if all

34:24.732 --> 34:28.000
of the most important people
in New York are here.

34:28.135 --> 34:30.002
Even still,
I didn't for the life of me

34:30.137 --> 34:31.804
imagine I'd meet you.

34:31.939 --> 34:33.138
It's quite the honor.

34:33.140 --> 34:35.808
- The honor is all mine.

34:35.943 --> 34:38.077
Indeed.

34:38.079 --> 34:41.013
I would very much like to--

34:41.148 --> 34:42.481
perhaps we could discuss--

34:42.617 --> 34:45.550
- My card.

34:45.552 --> 34:47.352
Do call on me.

34:47.354 --> 34:50.555
<i> [classical music]</i>

34:50.557 --> 34:56.762
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:56.897 --> 34:59.098
- [chuckles softly]

34:59.233 --> 35:06.372
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:38.673 --> 35:40.939
- Richard?

35:40.941 --> 35:43.208
Richard!

35:43.344 --> 35:45.611
Why didn't you come to me?

35:45.746 --> 35:47.680
Didn't you know
what happened to me?

35:47.815 --> 35:48.681
Where have you been?

35:48.816 --> 35:51.150
- Helen?
Come, now, Helen.

35:51.152 --> 35:52.485
- I want to talk to Richard.

35:52.619 --> 35:54.353
- [chuckling]
Too much champagne.

35:54.489 --> 35:56.822
- Get your hands
off her, Markoe.

35:56.957 --> 35:58.291
- She's deluded,
the poor creature.

35:58.425 --> 36:00.693
- Were you
in the Lying-In Hospital?

36:00.828 --> 36:02.161
If you touch her,

36:02.163 --> 36:03.496
I will scream bloody murder
at the top of my lungs

36:03.631 --> 36:05.898
and then there will indeed
be a scandal.

36:06.033 --> 36:09.702
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

36:09.837 --> 36:11.636
What happened?

36:11.638 --> 36:14.507
- [sobbing]
They took my baby.

36:14.641 --> 36:17.176
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

36:17.178 --> 36:21.380
They fixed me so I can't
have children anymore.

36:21.382 --> 36:24.049
I thought he loved me.
- He does love you, Helen.

36:24.185 --> 36:25.584
And that's why he's asked me

36:25.720 --> 36:30.255
to accompany you in his
carriage to the townhouse.

36:30.391 --> 36:31.991
- What?
He--he said that?

36:32.126 --> 36:34.059
- Yes.

36:34.061 --> 36:35.328
- You sterilized her, Markoe?

36:35.462 --> 36:36.662
Is that what you do
to all of them?

36:36.797 --> 36:38.797
- She had an infection.
I saved her life.

36:38.933 --> 36:42.401
Helen, Helen.
Come.

36:42.403 --> 36:44.337
- Don't go with him, Helen.

36:44.471 --> 36:47.072
You can trust me.
I can help you.

36:47.074 --> 36:50.075
<i> [soft suspenseful music]</i>

36:50.077 --> 36:51.744
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

36:51.879 --> 36:54.547
- May I?

36:54.682 --> 36:57.550
<i> [classical music]</i>

36:57.685 --> 37:04.657
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

37:26.647 --> 37:28.247
[cigarette sizzles]

37:28.383 --> 37:29.515
- Shame on you.

37:33.387 --> 37:36.355
[dog barks distantly]

37:36.490 --> 37:39.358
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

37:39.493 --> 37:46.399
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

37:49.704 --> 37:52.805
[clock ticking]

38:11.459 --> 38:13.092
- [sighs]

38:15.663 --> 38:18.931
The events earlier this evening
were simply a distraction.

38:19.067 --> 38:21.333
There is a phenomenon
common in visual perception

38:21.335 --> 38:24.002
that when something
is drawing the eye's attention,

38:24.004 --> 38:26.004
an object, a source of light,

38:26.006 --> 38:28.140
we become almost blind
to surrounding objects.

38:28.276 --> 38:30.943
- The human eye cannot help
but fixate on certain stimuli.

38:31.079 --> 38:33.746
- And in such cases,
the person isn't even aware

38:33.748 --> 38:34.881
that their perception
is limited,

38:35.015 --> 38:36.282
so subtle is the effect.

38:36.417 --> 38:37.950
- The same can be true
of the mind.

38:37.952 --> 38:39.885
And so it is with us,
we have gone off-course.

38:40.020 --> 38:41.287
- What are you saying, Laszlo?

38:41.422 --> 38:43.221
That we are no closer
to finding the killer

38:43.223 --> 38:45.157
of Martha Napp's baby or
the kidnapper of Ana Linares?

38:45.159 --> 38:47.159
That Markoe has nothing
to do with it?

38:47.295 --> 38:48.761
- Precisely.

38:48.763 --> 38:51.497
Dr. Markoe created a miasma
of corruption at that hospital

38:51.632 --> 38:53.832
in which our killer is hiding.

38:53.968 --> 38:55.901
But that may be
the extent of it.

38:56.036 --> 38:58.036
- Señora Linares.

38:58.038 --> 38:59.638
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:59.774 --> 39:01.841
Please, have a seat.

39:03.778 --> 39:05.311
[baby crying]

39:05.446 --> 39:08.180
- Colleen.

39:08.182 --> 39:10.182
- One of them puked
all over the floor.

39:10.184 --> 39:12.118
I only cleaned it an hour ago.

39:12.252 --> 39:15.788
- I'll help you.
- Thanks.

39:15.790 --> 39:17.790
- Got any clothes?

39:17.792 --> 39:24.964
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:28.402 --> 39:31.470
I didn't mean anything
by what I said.

39:31.605 --> 39:35.608
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:35.743 --> 39:37.009
- I thank you for helping me,

39:37.145 --> 39:41.279
but remembering
is also a curse.

39:41.281 --> 39:43.950
There was someone there
at the hospital

39:44.084 --> 39:46.084
who did not behave
as they should.

39:46.086 --> 39:47.619
- A member
of the hospital staff?

39:47.621 --> 39:49.021
- Yes.

39:49.157 --> 39:50.889
- Was Eva able to describe her?

39:50.891 --> 39:53.759
- She was a woman
one did not notice at first,

39:53.894 --> 39:56.695
but she was watching
all the time.

39:56.697 --> 40:00.366
Staring at Ana,
not touching her,

40:00.501 --> 40:04.503
not caring for her,
but watching.

40:04.639 --> 40:07.439
She looked back at me
and she left the room.

40:07.441 --> 40:09.441
I knew she meant harm.

40:09.443 --> 40:12.911
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

40:13.047 --> 40:15.982
- She looked back at you?

40:16.116 --> 40:18.217
Not at Ava?

40:19.787 --> 40:22.121
- It's me.

40:23.791 --> 40:24.657
My God.

40:24.792 --> 40:26.324
- Señora Linares,

40:26.326 --> 40:28.995
the trauma and fear
had repressed your memories.

40:29.129 --> 40:31.730
Your mind has constructed
a narrative

40:31.866 --> 40:37.003
that placed Ava, and not you,
at the Lying-In Hospital.

40:37.137 --> 40:39.405
- It means that you saw
who took your baby.

40:40.808 --> 40:43.942
<i> ♪ </i>

40:43.944 --> 40:47.413
- Yes, I saw her face again...

40:49.017 --> 40:51.550
That day.

40:51.686 --> 40:58.557
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

40:58.693 --> 41:00.759
Right here.

41:00.761 --> 41:01.760
[flash lamp snaps, echoes]

41:01.762 --> 41:03.562
[wind howling]

41:03.698 --> 41:05.964
<i> [tense music]</i>

41:06.100 --> 41:08.201
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:10.571 --> 41:12.771
[babies crying]

41:12.907 --> 41:14.773
- You ever have a baby?

41:14.909 --> 41:17.843
<i> [soft dramatic music]</i>

41:17.978 --> 41:20.112
But he didn't make it?

41:20.114 --> 41:24.182
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:24.318 --> 41:27.119
[baby crying distantly]

41:27.121 --> 41:28.454
Can you have another one?

41:28.589 --> 41:31.790
- You mean did they sew up
my tubes like the others?

41:31.926 --> 41:34.793
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:34.929 --> 41:37.195
They tried to, but I--

41:37.331 --> 41:39.932
I lost a lot of blood,
so they had to leave me intact.

41:39.934 --> 41:44.002
- [cries loudly]
- Libby told me.

41:44.004 --> 41:47.874
[baby cooing]

41:48.008 --> 41:50.609
- Colleen?

41:50.611 --> 41:53.145
What happened
to Martha Napp's baby?

41:53.147 --> 41:55.814
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

41:55.950 --> 41:57.283
- Sorry I'm late.
I have them.

41:57.418 --> 42:00.486
He printed them all
from that Tuesday.

42:00.621 --> 42:06.359
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:10.431 --> 42:12.030
- Do you recognize anyone?

42:12.166 --> 42:16.769
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:16.904 --> 42:18.704
- [gasps]
It's her.

42:18.839 --> 42:23.241
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:23.243 --> 42:26.244
<i> [dramatic notes]</i>

42:26.246 --> 42:27.780
- Oh, my God.

42:27.782 --> 42:31.049
- You know something?
You're a real nosy parker.

42:31.051 --> 42:33.051
- Colleen--
- I didn't do anything!

42:33.053 --> 42:34.186
And they're all blaming me.

42:34.322 --> 42:35.521
I checked on the baby
and she was there.

42:35.656 --> 42:36.789
Next, I heard her screaming.

42:36.791 --> 42:37.924
How was I to know
what happened?

42:38.058 --> 42:39.191
- But do you know
what happened?

42:39.327 --> 42:40.859
- No!
You're always asking questions!

42:40.995 --> 42:42.328
Blaming me?
What do you want?

42:42.463 --> 42:44.130
Get me thrown out, put in jail?
What are you, a snitch?

42:44.264 --> 42:45.597
- No!
[bucket clatters loudly]

42:45.599 --> 42:48.066
[both yelling]

42:48.202 --> 42:50.068
- [grunts]

42:50.070 --> 42:52.070
[horse neighs]

42:52.072 --> 42:53.940
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:54.074 --> 42:56.142
- The Lying-In Hospital.
- Please hurry!

42:56.277 --> 42:57.944
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:58.078 --> 43:00.279
- Come on!
Go!

43:00.414 --> 43:01.948
Yah!

43:02.082 --> 43:03.950
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

43:04.084 --> 43:06.485
- Come back, snitch!

43:06.620 --> 43:10.556
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

43:10.691 --> 43:12.024
- [yells]

43:12.160 --> 43:15.627
Open the door!
Open the door.

43:15.629 --> 43:18.096
You can't stay in there
forever!

43:18.232 --> 43:22.468
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

43:24.438 --> 43:27.173
- Libby,
Colleen's lost her mind.

43:27.307 --> 43:31.177
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

43:31.311 --> 43:32.911
- Has she?

43:33.047 --> 43:36.448
<i> [ominous notes]</i>

43:36.450 --> 43:39.051
- Go, go!

43:39.053 --> 43:43.222
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

43:47.862 --> 43:50.329
- Your mouth--
that's charcoal, isn't it?

43:50.464 --> 43:55.133
- You sure do ask
a lot of questions.

43:55.135 --> 43:56.068
- [groans]

43:56.204 --> 43:59.071
<i> [intense music]</i>

43:59.207 --> 44:02.541
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:02.677 --> 44:03.876
[yelps]

44:03.878 --> 44:09.815
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:09.950 --> 44:11.283
- Oh, God!

44:11.285 --> 44:13.085
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:13.087 --> 44:15.755
- Whoa!

44:17.758 --> 44:24.630
<i> ♪ </i>

44:28.703 --> 44:29.836
- Libby!

44:29.970 --> 44:33.239
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:33.374 --> 44:36.442
<i> [soft tense music]</i>

44:36.577 --> 44:37.910
- Doctor!

44:37.912 --> 44:40.079
[alarm ringing]

44:42.383 --> 44:43.916
- I tried to help her.

44:43.918 --> 44:45.251
- What happened?

44:45.386 --> 44:46.785
- Libby locked the door.
I couldn't get in.

44:46.787 --> 44:49.655
- Which way did she go?
- I don't know, she ran.

44:49.790 --> 44:51.590
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:51.592 --> 44:53.392
- She only managed
a partial syringe.

44:53.394 --> 44:56.729
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

44:56.731 --> 44:58.064
- Hurry.

44:58.198 --> 45:05.371
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

45:10.545 --> 45:13.812
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

45:13.814 --> 45:20.753
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

45:30.164 --> 45:32.631
- I tried to get in
and stop her, but I couldn't.

45:32.633 --> 45:34.232
- You did your best, Colleen.

45:34.368 --> 45:36.302
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

45:36.437 --> 45:39.171
- She's gone.

45:39.307 --> 45:41.039
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

45:41.175 --> 45:43.041
- Lucius.

45:43.177 --> 45:50.283
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:04.132 --> 46:06.265
- You're alive.

46:06.400 --> 46:07.666
You're alive.

46:07.802 --> 46:10.669
<i> [stirring music]</i>

46:10.805 --> 46:14.207
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:22.983 --> 46:24.717
- [knocks softly]

46:24.852 --> 46:27.720
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

46:27.855 --> 46:29.121
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:29.257 --> 46:30.989
[knocks loudly]

46:30.991 --> 46:32.791
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:32.927 --> 46:34.060
- Libby?

46:34.194 --> 46:36.662
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:36.797 --> 46:40.066
Excuse me?

46:40.200 --> 46:42.200
What are you doing?

46:42.202 --> 46:44.871
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:45.005 --> 46:47.873
I-I am calling the police.

46:48.008 --> 46:50.008
[yelps]

46:50.010 --> 46:51.477
- [sniffles]

46:51.612 --> 46:55.013
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

46:55.149 --> 46:57.483
- I'll give you, uh...

46:57.618 --> 46:59.818
I'll give you ten seconds
to leave, or--

46:59.954 --> 47:01.587
- Or what?

47:03.291 --> 47:06.024
You'll tell someone?
[chuckles]

47:06.026 --> 47:08.961
You'll--you'll scream?

47:09.097 --> 47:11.830
You'll what?

47:11.832 --> 47:14.100
[sighs]
So.

47:14.234 --> 47:17.503
So this is where you live?
[chuckles]

47:17.638 --> 47:22.441
You know, it, um,
it looks matronly.

47:22.443 --> 47:25.511
Perhaps too cluttered,
maybe a little cheap.

47:25.646 --> 47:29.515
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

47:29.650 --> 47:33.185
- What do you want?
- [laughing] I want?

47:33.187 --> 47:35.053
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

47:35.189 --> 47:37.923
I want to, um,

47:38.058 --> 47:41.527
um...
[chuckles shakily]

47:41.662 --> 47:43.929
To come in.

47:44.064 --> 47:45.932
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

47:46.066 --> 47:48.134
To, um, hmm.

47:48.269 --> 47:50.136
To lighten the load.

47:50.271 --> 47:52.805
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

47:52.807 --> 47:54.740
To, um,

47:54.875 --> 47:59.678
to rest my weary bones.

47:59.680 --> 48:04.350
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

48:04.485 --> 48:07.620
To find sanctuary.

48:07.755 --> 48:09.956
- Sanctuary?

48:10.090 --> 48:12.491
What have--
what have you done, Libby?

48:12.626 --> 48:15.294
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

48:15.429 --> 48:18.897
<i> [tense music]</i>

48:19.033 --> 48:20.232
[softly]
I can't breathe.

48:20.234 --> 48:21.633
- Do you understand
the feeling now?

48:21.635 --> 48:22.835
- I can't breathe.

48:22.837 --> 48:24.370
- That you gave
to all the girls around you?

48:24.505 --> 48:29.175
The stain you made on them?

48:29.309 --> 48:32.979
The life that you tore
from them?

48:33.113 --> 48:34.713
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

48:34.849 --> 48:38.851
How does it feel now to plead
for mercy with your eyes

48:38.853 --> 48:44.723
because your words,
even if they came,

48:44.859 --> 48:46.792
they mean nothing?

48:49.129 --> 48:52.264
- [groaning and choking]

48:52.266 --> 48:54.667
- Stupid...

48:54.802 --> 48:57.736
stupid...

48:57.738 --> 49:00.806
stupid.

49:00.941 --> 49:03.809
<i> [ominous music]</i>

49:03.944 --> 49:10.816
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

49:13.153 --> 49:18.324
[humming]

49:52.727 --> 49:57.630
[humming softly]
